SIMPLE: runt
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Runt
<hw>Runt</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>rant</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[Scot. <ets>runt</ets> an old cow, an
old, withered woman, a hardened stem or stalk, the trunk of a tree; cf.
D. <ets>rund</ets> a bullock, an ox or cow, G. <ets>rind</ets>. Cf.
<er>Rother</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>
<def>Any animal which is unusually small, as compared with others of its
kind; -- applied particularly to domestic animals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A variety of domestic pigeon,
related to the barb and carrier.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A dwarf; also, a mean, despicable, boorish person;
-- used opprobriously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before I buy a bargain of such <qex>runts</qex>,⟦br⟧
I'll buy a college for bears, and live among 'em.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The dead stump of a tree; also, the stem of a
plant.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither young poles nor old <qex>runts</qex> are durable.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Runty</ent>⟦br⟧
